sec.p:
The IDSA guidelines provide evidence-based recommendations for distinguishing bacterial, viral, and Mycoplasma pneumonia in children. Below are the key diagnostic criteria for each type:
Bacterial pneumonia
Clinical features:
Acute onset with high-grade fever (> 39 °C);
Tachypnea, chest pain, focal crackles, or signs of consolidation (e.g., dullness to percussion);
Systemic toxicity (lethargy, poor perfusion).
Laboratory findings:
Leukocytosis (> 15,000/µL) with neutrophilic predominance;
Markedly elevated inflammatory markers (C-reactive protein [CRP] > 40–60 mg/L; procalcitonin > 0.5 ng/mL).
Radiological features (Chest X-ray):
Lobar/segmental consolidation;
Pleural effusion (highly specific for bacterial etiology).
Microbiological confirmation:
Positive blood culture (detection rate: 1.4–11.4% in hospitalized children);
Pathogen identification from pleural fluid culture/polymerase chain reaction (PCR; e.g., Streptococcus pneumonia, Staphylococcus aureus).
Viral pneumonia
Clinical features:
Predominance in children < 5 years;
Preceding upper respiratory infection symptoms (rhinorrhea, cough);
Wheezing with low-grade fever (< 38.5 °C).
Laboratory findings:
Normal/mildly elevated white blood cell count (lymphocytic predominance);
CRP and procalcitonin typically within normal range.
Radiological features (Chest X-ray):
Bilateral interstitial infiltrates;
Patchy perihilar opacities.
Microbiological confirmation:
Positive nasopharyngeal swab PCR/antigen testing (e.g., influenza, respiratory syncytial virus, adenovirus).
Mycoplasma pneumonia Pneumonia
Clinical features:
Predominance in school-aged children/adolescents;
Insidious onset with persistent dry cough (> 1 week);
Clinical-radiographic dissociation: paucity of auscultatory findings despite significant radiographic abnormalities.
Laboratory findings:
Positive M. pneumonia-specific IgM serology (ELISA/rapid immunoassay);
PCR detection in respiratory specimens (e.g., sputum, throat swab).
Radiological features (Chest X-ray):
Unilateral patchy consolidation or peribronchial infiltrates;
Lobar consolidation uncommon (< 15% of cases).
